xxl.core.cursors.wrappers

Class IteratorCursor<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • xxl.core.cursors.AbstractCursor<E>
      • xxl.core.cursors.wrappers.IteratorCursor<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of the elements returned by this iteration.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterator<E>, Cursor<E>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Replicator

    public class IteratorCursor<E>
extends AbstractCursor<E>
    The iterator-cursor wraps an iterator to a cursor, i.e., the wrapped iterator can be accessed via the cursor interface. An iterator-cursor tries to pass all method calls to the underlying iterator. If an operation is not supported by the underlying iterator (update and reset) an UnsupportedOperationException is thrown.
    See Also:
    Iterator, Cursor, AbstractCursor

      • nextObject

        protected E nextObject()
        Returns the next element in the iteration. This element will be accessible by some of the iterator-cursor's methods, e.g., update or remove, until a call to next or peek occurs. This is calling next or peek proceeds the iteration and therefore its previous element will not be accessible any more.
        Specified by:

      • remove

        public void remove()
            throws IllegalStateException,
                   UnsupportedOperationException
        Removes from the underlying data structure the last element returned by the iterator-cursor (optional operation). This method can be called only once per call to next or peek and removes the element returned by this method. Note, that between a call to next and remove the invocation of peek or hasNext is forbidden. The behaviour of an iterator-cursor is unspecified if the underlying data structure is modified while the iteration is in progress in any way other than by calling this method.

        Note, that this operation is optional and might not work for all cursors.

        Specified by:
        remove in interface Iterator<E>
        Specified by:
        remove in interface Cursor<E>
        Overrides:
        remove in class AbstractCursor<E>
        Throws:
        IllegalStateException - if the next or peek method has not yet been called, or the remove method has already been called after the last call to the next or peek method.
        UnsupportedOperationException - if the remove operation is not supported by the iterator-cursor.
